happened today, right,

00:42:01.650 --> 00:42:03.566
there would be all this
copyright, oh my gosh,

00:42:03.566 --> 00:42:04.724
people are selling my book.

00:42:04.724 --> 00:42:06.390
So was they're not--
I mean, were people

00:42:06.390 --> 00:42:08.067
not trying to earn money?

00:42:08.067 --> 00:42:10.150
There's definitely some
difference here, I'm not--

00:42:10.150 --> 00:42:11.608
TOM STANDAGE: Yeah
no, that's true.

00:42:11.608 --> 00:42:14.370
So I mean, copyrights are
a relatively modern idea.

00:42:14.370 --> 00:42:17.140
It goes back to the beginning
of the 18th century.

00:42:17.140 --> 00:42:20.440
And so Roman authors
didn't expect

00:42:20.440 --> 00:42:22.190
to be able to make
money because they knew

00:42:22.190 --> 00:42:24.150
that the only way to
get their book out

00:42:24.150 --> 00:42:27.340
there was unrestricted
copying by the audience.

00:42:27.340 --> 00:42:30.129
And that was-- they
couldn't imagine

00:42:30.129 --> 00:42:31.420
that any other way of doing it.

00:42:31.420 --> 00:42:35.830
And they wrote books with a
view to becoming more famous,

00:42:35.830 --> 00:42:39.600
winning patronage,
getting a nice job.

00:42:39.600 --> 00:42:42.900
And that's how they
benefited from them.

00:42:42.900 --> 00:42:46.220
So that's clearly a different
way of doing things.

00:42:46.220 --> 00:42:48.400
What then later
happens with printing

00:42:48.400 --> 00:42:51.350
is that pamphleteers
would be paid

00:42:51.350 --> 00:42:53.220
little or nothing
to write pamphlets.

00:42:53.220 --> 00:42:56.849
They would be paid in the form
of copies of their pamphlets

00:42:56.849 --> 00:42:58.140
that they could give to people.

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:00.380
And again, it was
a patronage thing.

00:43:00.380 --> 00:43:02.740
So it's rather like the
deal I have with Wordpress.

00:43:02.740 --> 00:43:06.320
Which is that I don't pay
them, but I give them content

00:43:06.320 --> 00:43:09.070
and then they gave
me distribution.

00:43:09.070 --> 00:43:12.150
So I'm paid back in the
ability to reach an audience.

00:43:12.150 --> 00:43:14.990
So that's quite a similar model.

00:43:14.990 --> 00:43:17.250
And this idea that you own
stuff and you have a right

00:43:17.250 --> 00:43:20.400
to make money from it is
actually quite recent.

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:22.790
And as we can see, it
it's now become harder

00:43:22.790 --> 00:43:25.980
to enforce than it used to be.

00:43:25.980 --> 00:43:28.050
So that sort of
ownership of content

00:43:28.050 --> 00:43:32.800
is very much a mass media
way of looking at the world.

00:43:32.800 --> 00:43:36.350
And we do see some
people asking,

00:43:36.350 --> 00:43:37.715
how you look beyond that?

00:43:37.715 --> 00:43:40.347
Should you have your music on
Spotify and then make money?

00:43:40.347 --> 00:43:42.180
But you hardly make
anything from it at all.

00:43:42.180 --> 00:43:44.690
And make money from other
things if you're a musician?

00:43:44.690 --> 00:43:45.950
And to what extent?

00:43:45.950 --> 00:43:50.580
Cory Doctorow gives away
his books as ebooks.

00:43:50.580 --> 00:43:53.620
And we're all trying to work
out what the sort of new models

00:43:53.620 --> 00:43:54.400
are around that.

00:43:54.400 --> 00:43:56.240
But there were
people in the past

00:43:56.240 --> 00:43:59.170
you managed to make a
living from doing things

00:43:59.170 --> 00:44:00.550
in a sort of indirect way.

00:44:00.550 --> 00:44:03.890
So maybe we can borrow
some of their models.

